[[en:Standing Pit Tomb]]

<!--Standing Pit Tomb--><!--Standing Pit Tomb--><!--Standing Pit Tomb--><!--Standing Pit Tomb--><!--Standing Pit Tomb--><!--Standing Pit Tomb--><!--Standing Pit Tomb-->

[[File:立石土壙墓.png|thumb|Schematic diagram of Tateishi Doko Bo]]
'''Tateishi Doko Bo''' (立石土壙墓) refers to a type of '''{{ill|Pit graves|ja|土壙墓|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Pit graves|qq=}}''' (pit-grave burial), where one or more '''long, flat stones''' are erected in front of the burial site. This burial custom was practiced from the '''late Middle Yayoi period''' to the '''early Kofun period''', specifically in the '''southern tip of the Satsuma Peninsula''' in '''Kagoshima Prefecture, Kyushu'''. The most well-known examples are from the '''{{ill|Narikawa Ruins|ja|成川遺跡|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Narikawa Ruins|qq=}}''' in '''[[:en:Ibusuki|Ibusuki, Kagoshima]]''', Yamakawa Narikawa.

== Overview ==

A '''pit-shaped grave''' was dug into the ground, and after the deceased was buried, a '''long, flat stone''' was erected nearby. Some instances feature '''one stone per grave''', while others have '''a single stone for multiple graves''' clustered together. It is believed that these stones functioned as '''grave markers''', either for individuals or collective burials.{{Sfn|Tamura|1974}}

== Grave Goods ==

Few '''grave goods''' were found within the burial pits themselves. However, in some cases, '''pottery and other offerings''' were placed on the surface '''after burial''' (e.g., '''{{ill|Minami-Surugahama Ruins|ja|南摺ヶ浜遺跡|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minami-Surugahama Ruins|qq=}}''' in Ibusuki).{{Sfn|Kagoshima Prefectural Archaeological Center|2007}}

At the '''Narikawa Ruins''', '''iron weapons''' such as '''iron swords''', '''iron arrowheads''', '''{{ill|Jakoken|ja|蛇行剣|1=Dakōken|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jakoken|13=User:Immanuelle/Dakōken|qq=}}''' (serpentine swords), and '''curved-blade swords''' (deliberately bent straight swords) have been found, along with '''unusual iron objects'''.{{Sfn|Tamura|1974}} However, these artifacts were discovered '''scattered around the burial pits''', rather than being placed within individual graves as personal burial goods.{{Sfn|Hashimoto|Fujii|2007|pp=55–62}} As a result, scholars suggest that these weapons were '''offerings made to collective graves''', rather than personal belongings of the deceased.

== Distribution ==

Beyond the '''Narikawa Ruins''', Tateishi Doko Bo burials have also been discovered at:
* '''{{ill|Minami-Surugahama Ruins|ja|南摺ヶ浜遺跡|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minami-Surugahama Ruins|qq=}}''' (14 stone markers) in '''Ibusuki'''{{Sfn|Kagoshima Prefectural Archaeological Center|2009}}
* '''{{ill|Matsuno-o Ruins|ja|松之尾遺跡|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Matsuno-o Ruins|qq=}}''' (6 stone markers) in '''[[:en:Makurazaki, Kagoshima|Makurazaki, Kagoshima]]'''{{Sfn|Makurazaki City Board of Education|1981}}

This burial style is '''unique to the southern tip of the Satsuma Peninsula'''. The origin of the '''standing stones''' is unclear, but since these graves '''always coexisted''' with '''other types of pit burials''' and '''pottery-coffin burials''', Tateishi Doko Bo is considered a '''localized variation''' of the broader '''Doko Bo''' burial tradition.

